						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="bold">King: <hi rend="italic">Madiraikoṇḍa kop-Parakēsari</hi> (Parāntaka I) Year 35: 942 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>It contains two parts. The middle portion of the record is erased. The first part seems to record some gift for feeding a brāhmaṇa well-versed in vēdas, when the god of Tiruvoṟṟiyūr was served mid-day food offerings.</p>						

						<p>The second section records that Ilāḍaippēraraiyaṉ <hi rend="italic">alias</hi> Chōḷasikhāmaṇippallavaraiyar made a gift fifty <hi rend="italic">kaḻañju</hi> of gold tested by the touchstone of the <hi rend="italic">ūr (ūrkaṟ-semmai)</hi>, for feeding two <hi rend="italic">mahāvritigaḷ</hi>, when the god of Tiruvoṟṟiyūr was served food offerings during the mid day. The <hi rend="italic">bhaṭārar</hi> (temple priests ?) and temple servants <hi rend="italic">(dēvakanmigaḷ)</hi> received the gold and agreed to supply (necessary items required for this purpose) at the temple treasury.</p>						

						</summary>
